      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I can help you with that. To wrap up any active indexing/caching tasks, I recommend running the following commands:\n\n1. Stop any active indexing tasks by running `pg_stopindex <database_name>`. This will stop any ongoing index rebuilds or maintenance tasks.\n2. Clear any cache using `pg_cache_clear <database_name>`. This will remove any cached data that might interfere with the full state wipe.\n3. Run `pg_dump <database_name> --clean` to dump the database and remove any unnecessary data.\n4. Stop any active caching layers by running `nginx-stop` or `apache-stop` depending on your web server configuration.\n5. Run `pmset usage` on macOS or `tasklist` on Windows to check for any running processes that might be using system resources.\n\nAdditionally, you can also use the following command to stop any background processes:\n\n`pg_ctl stop -D <database_directory>`\n\nReplace `<database_name>` with the actual name of your database and `<database_directory>` with the directory where your database files are located.\n\nOnce you've completed these steps, you should be able to run the full state wipe script without any issues.",
